        <h1>University of Edinburgh</h1>
        <figure  class="right-wider-image"><a href="https://cantaloupe.is.ed.ac.uk/iiif/2/umis-visit-edinburgh.jpg/full/full/0/default.jpg" target="_blank"  title="University of Edinburgh St Cecilia's Hall"><img src="https://cantaloupe.is.ed.ac.uk/iiif/2/umis-visit-edinburgh.jpg/full/300,/0/default.jpg" alt-text="University of Edinburgh St Cecilia's Hall" /></a></figure>
        <p>Edinburgh University&rsquo;s extensive collections span art, musical instruments, medicine and anatomy, natural history, geology and the University&rsquo;s archives as well as the Edinburgh College of Art collection and much more.</p>
        <p>Visit the collections online at <a href="https://collections.ed.ac.uk/"  target="_blank" title="Collections">https://collections.ed.ac.uk/</a></p>
        <h3>Visiting:</h3>
        <p>For general information on visiting the University&rsquo;s museums, including accessibility information, visit <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries"  target="_blank" title="Museums and Galleries">https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries</a></p>
        <p>To find out about all the exhibitions and events being run by the University&rsquo;s collections, visit <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/exhibitions"  target="_blank" title="Exhibitions">https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/exhibitions</a></p>
        <p>There are various locations within the University campus to see the collections:</p>
        <h2><a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/anatomical"  target="_blank"  title="Anatomical Museum">Anatomical Museum</a></h2>
        <p>This collection of anatomy, pathology, and zoology contains over 12,000 objects which tell the story of 300 years of teaching at the University. The museums have permanent displays including anatomical teaching models, human skeletons and dried and fluid preserved specimens.&nbsp;</p>
        <p><strong>PLEASE NOTE: </strong>Some of the displays contain human and other remains and might be unsettling to certain visitors.</p>
        <h3>Address:</h3>
        <p>Doorway 3, Medical School, Teviot Place, Edinburgh EH8 9AG</p>
        <h3>Opening hours:</h3>
        <p>The museum is only open to visitors on certain days of the year. On these days, entry is free and there is no need to book. For specific opening information, please visit <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/anatomical"  target="_blank" title="Anatomical Museum">https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/anatomical</a></p>
        <h3>Group and school visits:</h3>
        <p>To arrange a group or school visit email <a href="mailto:museums@ed.ac.uk">museums@ed.ac.uk</a> or call 0131 650 2600 (phone manned Tuesday &ndash; Saturday 10am &ndash; 5pm)</p>
        <h3>Research visits:</h3>
        <p>Please contact the museum directly to enquire about research visits. Email Malcolm MacCallum, Anatomical Museum Curator/Researcher on <a href="mailto:Malcolm.maccallum@ed.ac.uk">Malcolm.maccallum@ed.ac.uk</a> or call 0131 650 2989</p>
        <h3>Getting there:</h3>
        <p>The museum is housed within the Old Medical School building on Teviot Place between McEwan Hall and middle meadow walk.</p>
        <p>Entrance to the museum is through the archway on Teviot Place, then across to Doorway 3. A ramp allows access through Doorway 3.</p>
        <p>There are two disabled parking spaces on site. Otherwise visitors can pay and display in the surrounding streets.</p>
        <p>To find out about bus links, visit <a href="http://www.lothianbuses.com"  target="_blank" title="Lothian Buses">www.lothianbuses.com</a></p>
        <h3>Accessibility:</h3>
        <p>A lift is available to the museum (3rd floor) and also the anatomy lecture theatre and elephant skeletons (1st floor).</p>
        <p>Two disabled parking spaces in the courtyard in front of the museum entrance at Doorway 3.</p>
        <p>Visit the <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/anatomical"  target="_blank" title="Anatomical Museum">University&rsquo;s website</a> for specific directions.</p>
        <h2><a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/information-services/library-museum-gallery/crc"  target="_blank" title="Centre for Research Collections">Centre for Research Collections</a></h2>
        <p>The Centre is a dedicated space to use and research the University&rsquo;s historic collections. The centre offers access to and use of the rare books, manuscripts, archives, art and musical instrument collections. It is based on the 6<sup>th</sup> Floor of the University Library.</p>
        <h3>Address:</h3>
        <p>Main University Library, George Square, Edinburgh EH8 9LJ</p>
        <h3>Opening hours:</h3>
        <p>Opening times are based on the academic timetables due to its use in teaching and research. For specific opening information, visit <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/research-collections" target="_blank"  title="Research Collections">https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/research-collections</a></p>
        <p>To use the facility, you&rsquo;ll need to make an appointment. Please contact them on <a href="mailto:is-crc@ed.ac.uk">is-crc@ed.ac.uk</a></p>
        <h3>Getting there:</h3>
        <p>There are a limited number of disabled parking spaces adjacent to George Square. In addition, there is ample pay and display parking in the square and surrounding streets.</p>
        <p>To find out about bus links, visit <a href="http://www.lothianbuses.com"  target="_blank" title="Lothian Buses">www.lothianbuses.com</a></p>
        <p>Visit the <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/research-collections"  target="_blank" title="Research Collections">University&rsquo;s website</a> for specific directions and access information.</p>
        <h2><a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/geology"  target="_blank" title="Cockburn Geological Museum">Cockburn Geological Museum</a></h2>
        <p>The collection includes over 130,000 objects such as minerals, rocks and fossils. Many of the objects from the collection are displayed in cabinets throughout the corridors of the Grant Institute.</p>
        <h3>Address:</h3>
        <p>School of GeoSciences, Grant Institute, James Hutton Road, King&rsquo;s Buildings, Edinburgh EH9 3FE</p>
        <h3>Opening hours:</h3>
        <p>If you&rsquo;d like to visit as an individual or group, book a hosted tour, or would like to arrange a research visit, please contact the Curator via email <a href="mailto:cockburnmuseum@ed.ac.uk">cockburnmuseum@ed.ac.uk</a> or call on 0131 650 8536. The Grant Institute is open Monday &ndash; Friday, 9am &ndash; 5pm.</p>
        <h3>Getting there:</h3>
        <p>There is disabled parking within the Kings Buildings campus and free on road parking in the surrounding area.</p>
        <p>To find out about bus links, visit <a href="http://www.lothianbuses.com"  target="_blank" title="Lothian Buses">www.lothianbuses.com</a></p>
        <p>Visit the <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/geology"  target="_blank" title="Cockburn Geological Museum">University&rsquo;s website</a> for specific directions and access information</p>
        <h2><a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/natural"  target="_blank" title="Natural History Collections">Natural History Collections</a></h2>
        <p>These collections include a wide range of zoology specimens and objects that have been collected over the last 300 years. The collections are housed in the Ashworth Laboratories, within the King&rsquo;s Buildings campus of the University.</p>
        <h3>Address:</h3>
        <p>Ashworth Laboratories, Charlotte Auerbach Road, King&rsquo;s Buildings, Edinburgh EH9 3FL</p>
        <h3>Opening hours:</h3>
        <p>If you&rsquo;d like to visit as an individual or group, or would like to arrange a research visit, please contact the museum Curators directly &ndash; either Mark Blaxter on <a href="mailto:mark.blaxter@ed.ac.uk">mark.blaxter@ed.ac.uk</a> or Graham Stone on <a href="mailto:graham.stone@ed.ac.uk">graham.stone@ed.ac.uk</a></p>
        <h3>Getting there:</h3>
        <p>There is disabled parking within the Kings Buildings campus and free on road parking in the surrounding area.</p>
        <p>To find out about bus links, visit <a href="http://www.lothianbuses.com"  target="_blank" title="Lothian Buses">www.lothianbuses.com</a></p>
        <p>Visit the <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/natural"  target="_blank" title="Natural History Collections">University&rsquo;s website</a> for specific directions and access information.</p>
        <h2><a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/talbot"  target="_blank" title="Talbot Rice Gallery">Talbot Rice Gallery</a></h2>
        <p>Largely a gallery focusing on contemporary visual art, the Talbot Rice Gallery is the public gallery of the University. Works on display span a huge range of work from contemporary and experimental emerging artists to historic and academic exhibitions.&nbsp;</p>
        <p>The gallery houses both changing exhibitions and permanent displays, as well as providing a dedicated space to support early career artists, residencies and experimental projects.</p>
        <h3>Address:</h3>
        <p>Old College, South Bridge, Edinburgh EH8 9YL</p>
        <h3>Opening hours:</h3>
        <p>Entry to the gallery is free and you won&rsquo;t have to book. Opening hours/days vary according to exhibition schedules. For details on specific opening times and current and scheduled exhibitions, visit the gallery&rsquo;s website at <a href="https://www.trg.ed.ac.uk/"  target="_blank" alt-text="Talbot Rice Gallery" title="Talbot Rice Gallery">https://www.trg.ed.ac.uk/</a></p>
        <h3>Getting there:</h3>
        <p>There is no parking on site, but ample pay and display in the surrounding areas.</p>
        <p>To find out about bus links, visit <a href="http://www.lothianbuses.com"  target="_blank" title="Lothian Buses">www.lothianbuses.com</a></p>
        <p>Visit the <a href="https://www.ed.ac.uk/visit/museums-galleries/talbot" target="_blank" title="Talbot Rice Gallery">University&rsquo;s website</a> for specific directions and access information.</p>
        <h2><a href="http://www.stcecilias.ed.ac.uk" target="_blank" title="St Cecilia's Hall">St Cecilia&rsquo;s Hall: Concert Room and Music Museum</a></h2>
        <p>St Cecilia&rsquo;s Hall, Scotland&rsquo;s oldest purpose built concert room, is one of the most recent additions to Edinburgh&rsquo;s visitor attractions, offering a range of public events, workshops, tours and concerts, as well as the University&rsquo;s music museum.</p>
        <p>The Musical Instrument Collection comprises around 6,000 items, of which over 500 from across the globe are on display, and you can even see the museum&rsquo;s conservator at work caring for the collection.</p>
        <h3>Address:</h3>
        <p>50 Niddry Street, Edinburgh EH1 1LG</p>
        <h3>Opening hours:</h3>
        <p>Entry to the museum is free. The museum is open:</p>
        <p>Tuesday &ndash; Saturday 10am-5pm (last admission 4.30pm)</p>
        <p>Information on special events can be found at <a href="http://www.stcecilias.ed.ac.uk/whats-on/"   target="_blank" title="What's On">http://www.stcecilias.ed.ac.uk/whats-on/</a></p>
        <p>The venue can also be hired for private events. For further information, visit <a href="http://www.stcecilias.ed.ac.uk/venue-hire/"   target="_blank" title="Venue Hire">http://www.stcecilias.ed.ac.uk/venue-hire/</a></p>
        <p>Information about the Musical Instrument Collection can be found at <a href="http://www.collections.ed.ac.uk/mimed" target="_blank" title="MIMEd">http://www.collections.ed.ac.uk/mimed</a></p>
        <h3>Group and school visits:</h3>
        <p>To book a group or school visit email <a href="mailto:museums@ed.ac.uk">museums@ed.ac.uk</a> or call 0131 650 2600 (phone manned Tuesday &ndash; Saturday 10am &ndash; 5pm)</p>
        <h3>Getting there:</h3>
        <p>Pay and display parking is available on the Cowgate and surrounding streets.</p>
        <p>Visit the <a href="http://www.stcecilias.ed.ac.uk/planning/"   target="_blank" title="Planning Your Visit">museum&rsquo;s website</a> for specific information on visiting, including accessibility and public transport.</p>
